Not sure if this also affects OpenGL implementation.

The bug is in `private void PlatformGetData<T>(int level, int arraySlice, Rectangle? rect, T[] data, int startIndex, int elementCount)` the `startIndex` parameter is used as in offset in the texture data instead of being an offset for the `data` parameter.

To reproduce the bug take any non transparent black texture and use this code

``` cs
Texture2D t= Texture2D.FromStream("whatever it is called");
Color[] colors=new Color[2];
t.GetData(0, new Rectangle(0,0,1,1), colors,1,1);
Assert.AreNotEqual(0, colors[1].A);
```

Will do a pull with the fix and the test shortly, but I have to test this a little with different rectangle sizes

When you have to initialize a bunch of colors the current setters and constructors are inefficient.  They all do internal math to scale or clamp values to back to a byte then pack them.  Often this math isn't needed but is there just in case someone passes an out of range value.

I suggest extending the API to support two additional constructors directly taking a packed value and channel bytes:

```
public Color(uint packedValue)
{
...
}

public Color(byte red, byte green, byte blue, byte alpha)
{
...
}
```

These would be the most efficient constructors one could use.

We should also document the packed format in the reference docs on the new ctor and the packed value getter/setter.
